docs.abstract: The former star is using social media savvy, and a total lack of interviews, to control the narrative of protests in the N.F.L.
docs.snippet: The former star is using social media savvy, and a total lack of interviews, to control the narrative of protests in the N.F.L.
docs.lead_paragraph: A tall, unemployed man took his niece to see Serena and Venus Williams play each other at the United States Open on Friday of last week. The man, a free-agent football player clad in a simple black T-shirt, was briefly shown on the video board at Arthur Ashe Stadium to thunderous applause from the crowd. His response was little more than a smile, enough to light up social media with messages of support.

headline.main: The Deafening Silence of Colin Kaepernick

docs.abstract: A 1976 TV movie that imagined years as people is a helpful reminder that a new page on the calendar is an arbitrary creation.
docs.snippet: A 1976 TV movie that imagined years as people is a helpful reminder that a new page on the calendar is an arbitrary creation.
docs.lead_paragraph: If 2020 were a person, what would it look like? I imagine someone tired, ravaged, beaten down by illness and police brutality, and weary from trying to stay afloat in a sinking economy. We’ve personified 2020 in articles and memes and GIFs, speaking of it as though it were a living, breathing antagonist in our collective story. And this past New Year’s celebration was not so much about the birth of a new year as about the death of an old one that no one asked for.

headline.main: Listen to Rudolph: A New Year Is Both a Comfort and a Fiction

docs.abstract: Stefon Bristol’s film imagines what “Back to the Future” might look like with a black cast. The stakes turn out to be significantly higher.
docs.snippet: Stefon Bristol’s film imagines what “Back to the Future” might look like with a black cast. The stakes turn out to be significantly higher.
docs.lead_paragraph: What would happen if “Back to the Future” starred black people? That’s what the filmmaker Stefon Bristol imagines in “See You Yesterday” (there’s even a winking cameo by Michael J. Fox), now on Netflix, which centers on C. J. (Eden Duncan-Smith), a high school science prodigy who builds a time-traveling backpack.

headline.main: ‘See You Yesterday’ Review: An All-Too-Real Time-Travel Fantasy

docs.abstract: Boris Johnson came into office aiming to defund the BBC and let in rivals. The coronavirus has delayed that, but the broadcaster again finds itself a punching bag for Conservatives.
docs.snippet: Boris Johnson came into office aiming to defund the BBC and let in rivals. The coronavirus has delayed that, but the broadcaster again finds itself a punching bag for Conservatives.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — It had all the ingredients for a juicy skirmish in Britain’s simmering culture war, so when the BBC announced last week that it would strip the lyrics from two popular patriotic songs in its telecast of a beloved annual concert, Conservative leaders predictably lined up to express their outrage.

headline.main: BBC Lost a Battle Over British Songs, and the War Is Far From Over
headline.print_headline: The BBC Loses a Battle Over Patriotic Songs, And the War Isn’t Over
